(29, 'Chapter 1', '<p>f) Normalization of the tables.</p><p><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;\">Physical Design Phases:</b></p><p>a) Creation of assets,</p><p>b) Realizing the form design and providing data entry,</p><p>c) Adapting the report design,</p><p>d) Writing support programs and user interface to facilitate database usage</p><p>e) Testing the database system and preparing documents.</p><p>Relational Databases</p><p>Almost all modern database management systems store and process information using the relational database management model. The term relational arises from the fact that each record in the database contains information about a single topic and only information related to that topic. If you examine the relational database management model, you will see that the relationship term applies only to a rowset on a topic. In addition, data related to two classes of information (such as customers and orders) can be managed as a whole depending on the associated data values. For example, it would be unnecessary to keep customer name and address information with every order the customer places. In a relational database system, there is a field that stores information about the orders, each order to the appropriate customer information, such as the customer number.</p><p>In the relational database management system (Relational Database Management System-RDBMS), the system manages all data in tables. Tables store information about a topic (such as customers and products). However, there are columns containing other relevant information (eg customers&#39; addresses or book titles) and rows that describe all the attributes of a single subject of the topic (for example, data about a particular customer or book). Even when we query the database (bringing information from one or more tables), the result is always something that looks like another table.</p><p><br></p><p>You can also combine related values from multiple tables or queries. For example, you can combine author and book information to find out which authors wrote which books. You can combine employee and contract information to find out which salesperson deserves a premium.</p><p>Relational database management system regulates the structure of databases. Thanks to this feature, it is possible to do the following:</p><p>&bull; Ensures that data are stored correctly and effectively.</p><p>&bull; Relational integrity rule (database integrity) is provided.</p><p>&bull; Thanks to the change records, it enables to recover data when the system crashes.</p><p>The purpose of the relational database model is high efficiency. For example, suppose we keep personnel information in a database. Staff name, address, phone information will be replicated for different departments where the staff works. This unnecessary redundancy leads to both increased disk space requirements and increased data access time issues when it comes to databases dealing with a significant number of records.</p><p>In the relational model, the data will be divided into two tables. The first table contains personal information such as insurance number, identity number, address, phone, age. The second table contains the departmental information in which the staff works instead of duplicating this information.</p><p>Database Skills</p><p>The relational database management system (RDBMS) allows you to fully control the issues of identifying, working with, and sharing your data. The system offers advanced features that make it easy to catalog and manage large numbers of data in many tables. RDBMS has three main skills: defining, managing and controlling data.</p><p>&bull; Data Definition: You can define what data is stored in the database, the data type (for example, numbers or characters) and the way the data is related. In some cases, you can define how the data should be formatted and validated.</p><p>&bull; Data Management: You can work with data in many ways. You can choose which data fields you want, filter and sort the data. You can combine (summarize) the data with related information. You can choose an information set and ask RDBMS to update it, delete it, copy it to a separate table or create a new table containing this data.</p><p>&bull; Data Control: You can define who can read, update or add data. In most cases, you can also define how data is shared and updated by multiple users.</p><p>All these functionalities are in the powerful features of Microsoft Access. Now let&#39;s look at how Access accomplished these skills and compare them with what you can do with spreadsheet or word processing programs.</p><p>Microsoft Access is a fully functional RDBMS. It provides all the data definition, management and auditing features you need to manage large numbers of data.</p><p>SQL (Structured Query Language)</p><p>It is known as the standard programming language of SQL database management systems. It is possible to use the SQL language in query windows within the Microsoft Access program or in Visual Basic programs.</p><p>SQL commands can be categorized under two headings:</p><p>1. DDL Commands (Database definition language)</p><p>2. DML Commands (Data processing language)</p><p>DDL Commands:</p><p>Create table: Provides the creation of fields and indexes of a new table.</p><p>Create index: Creates an index for the specified table.</p><p>Drop table: Deletes the specified tables and indexes from the database.</p><p>Alter table: Adds new fields to the table, allows changing field definitions.</p><p><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;\">DML Commands:</b></p><p><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;\">Select</b>: Enables selection of records in the table according to the specified criteria.</p><p><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;\">Insert</b>: Adds a new record in the table.</p><p><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;\">Update</b>: Updates the fields of the specified record.</p><p><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;\">Delete</b>: Deletes the specified records.</p><p>These commands cannot be used alone. Some auxiliary statements are needed to perform functions:</p><p><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;\">From:</b> Defines from which table the query will be made.</p><p><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;\">Where:</b> Defines the criterion to be used at the time of query.</p><p><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;\">Group By</b>: Groups records according to the specified area.</p><p><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;\">Having:</b> Defines the criterion that each group must comply with.</p><p><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;\">Order By</b>: Enables sorting of selected records.</p><p><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;\">Constraint</b>: It enables to define the index and establish a relationship with another table.</p><p>Example: Create table Table name (field names and types);</p><p>Drop table table name;</p><p>QBE (Query By Example)</p><p>QBE is an extension of different query languages. The purpose of QBE is to improve the user&#39;s query in a graphical environment without using a professional questioning language.</p><p>In other words, QBE is an inquiry technique. It is not a questioning language. QBE allows the user to develop a complex query that will answer questions.</p><p>QBE first starts by selecting the relevant tables from the database. Then, the columns to be questioned are determined. For example; Personnel address in a database is equal, not equal, greater, etc. in QBE lines. expressions are used. In addition, SQL commands can be used in QBE lines.</p>', '0', 1, 'chapter-1'),
